, what the WaPo does is not journalism?</p></p></p></div></div></div><div class="comment"><div class="commentnumber">12</div><div class="commenthead">5 points by <a class="userlink" rel="tzs">tzs</a> 6  days ago <a title="number and link to replies to this comment" href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=2043066">1 reply</a> <span  title="expand this comment" class="commentopener">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><div class='text'>Perhaps Wired is only releasing those parts of the logs that they are able to find some corroboration for. Considering the Salon author's prior poorly researched reporting on Manning, the idea of actually checking on things before publishing may be alien to him.</div></div></div><div class="comment"><div class="commentnumber">13</div><div class="commenthead">4 points by <a class="userlink" rel="Vivtek">Vivtek</a> 6  days ago <a title="number and link to replies to this comment" href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=2043366">0 replies</a> <span  title="expand this comment" class="commentopener">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><div class='text'>Does anybody but me find it sort of comic-booky that the head of Project Vigilant, a group surveilling the Internet so the government won't have to, is named "Uber"?</div></div></div><div class="comment"><div class="commentnumber">14</div><div class="commenthead">1 point by <a class="userlink" rel="DanielBMarkham">DanielBMarkham</a> 6  days ago <a title="number and link to replies to this comment" href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=2043676">1 reply</a> <span  title="expand this comment" class="commentopener">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><div class='text'>Okay I admit to skimming after the tenth paragraph or so, so if I screw up my response I apologize. The article just seemed very wordy, but not so substantive.<p>&#60;snark&#62;But am I to understand that the beef here is that wired is _not_ publishing something that others think they should? So now not only do we need a 